nucleus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprojects to subthalamic nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. The globus pallidus externa (GPe) sends inhibitory gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) projections to the subthalamic nucleus as part of the indirect pathway of motor control.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProjects to substantia nigra\u003C/strong\u003E - The substantia nigra receives input from the striatum, not the GPe\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProjects to motor cortex\u003C/strong\u003E - The GPe does not project directly to the motor cortex\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProjects to striatum\u003C/strong\u003E - While there are some minor connections, this is not the primary output\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProjects to thalamus\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the primary output of the globus pallidus interna, not the externa\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe GPe\u0027s projection to the subthalamic nucleus forms a crucial link in the indirect pathway of motor control, which ultimately modulates movement through thalamic influence on the motor cortex.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The globus pallidus externa primarily projects inhibitory signals to the subthalamic nucleus.","The globus pallidus interna sends inhibitory outputs to the thalamus as part of the indirect motor pathway.","Both segments of the globus pallidus use gamma-aminobutyric acid as their primary neurotransmitter."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62318"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id"